    <p>Further comments below:</p>

    <blockquote>
        <p><i>86: Eighty Six</i> has been in my mind for years before I started. For more than two years, a friend of mine has been pestering me to watch this series. And for years I've seen many arts of Lena, tempting me to get into a series that I started to piece together through osmosis.</p>

        <p>I know the series is about war. I know that at some point I thought this series is like Brandon Sanderson's 'Skyward' series. I know there's a romance here (or so I was told). But nothing that came before can really prepare me for what this series is really about once I started watching them.</p>
                
        <p>When I first watch this series, three series came to mind immediately that I have experienced before; Red Rising, All You Need Is Kill, and to a lesser degree, Top Gun.</p>

        <p>It does not take me long to love this series. The dual POV and how each POV blend into each other is expertly weaved to make the series so compelling, with each protagonist of each POV being so interesting. A somehow pure ojou-sama who is a rising ranking officer in the empire, and the cool, calm, and collected Captain of the... "undesirables", the Eighty-Sixes.</p>

        <p>Not much about this story that I should reveal to you. This story is too good for me to spoil you, so I'll just say aspect of the presentation that I really enjoyed. I enjoyed their use of smash cut to deliver the maximum emotional impact of a scene, which I can surmise is probably something that they adapt straight from the novels. I really love that they make sure to include nuance in a topic that would be very incendiary otherwise, and portrays topic in both idealistic point of view, and realistically. I very much enjoyed the action piece, which is mostly mecha but they're so cool!</p>

        <p>And yes, that Fido cutscene guts me too, alongside numerous other that I won't name because of spoiler reason. (Most are related to smash cuts, as I explained above. These bastards know what they're doing...)</p>

        <p>And also yes, the OST for this fucking SLAPS. Hiroyuki Sawano... you bastard... you always came through. The OP is a banger, and the fucking ED made me cry at the last episode... the songs are so good...</p>
    </blockquote>

