    <p>Further comments below:</p>

    <blockquote>
        <p><i>86: Eighty Six Part Two</i> continues the story after we left off... and took a completely different turn.</p>
    
        <p>Everything about this fictional world I know before is upturned as new setting beckons, with new people... and new challenges.</p>
    
        <p>In this part I learned much about how even the most peaceful country can still bring heartbreak to the Eighty-Sixes. Their rights as human are restored, but because of the way they lived, they cannot conceive of a life outside of the battlefield.</p>
                
        <p>And so they return and risk their life, as that is the only life they know. Such sorrow I feel when I thought they finally had escaped certain death. The series this time is a little less despair-filled, as the main cast has better lives now... but the greater the peace, the greater the suffering.</p>

        <p>The animation never cease to amaze me, as I think this part actually elevates the series as a whole. There's tons of hidden meaning in the way they frame each scenes, so much so that I am just completely in awe with how much is packed inside a 24 minute episodes and everything just never seemed to be rushed or bloated. Every second of the show is there for a reason.</p>

        <p>It's the kind of quality I would expect to come out of a movie, older movies, where they need to put care into their work due to limited "film" they can produce. This part though does ditch the unique two POVs that they have before after a few episodes, due to plot reasons, but they completely make it up by giving us even more unique characters in the wake of the void Lena left.</p>

        <p>The OP for this season (and the ED too, surprisingly, after a few listen) is still so fucking good. I love the animation part where they transform a still image of whatever we see last into this graffiti like art. I really enjoyed how this anime WILL skip OP/ED entirely if they needed more time for the story. I find series that are willing to do that to be slightly superior, as the studio made the call to add MORE animation in order to not mess up with the flow of the story. </p>

        <p>By the end, I was completely shedding tears at the struggle our Reaper has with himself and his reason to live (while "Voices of the Chord", the season 2 version of that first season ED is playing... man...) and the ending that probably ranked pretty high in the list of animes that I've watched... and successfully managed to make me want to read the light novel. GODDAMN THIS SHOW IS SO GOOD. I CAN FINALLY JOIN EVERYONE WHO KEEP ASKING A-1 PICTURES ABOUT SEASON 2. WHERE IS SEASON 2?????</p>
    </blockquote>
            
